00:05:39.350 --> 00:05:42.800
I'll know talk about some of
the elements of the blockchain

00:05:42.800 --> 00:05:45.460
now I've increased your
interest, hopefully.

00:05:45.460 --> 00:05:50.330
So a blockchain is
simply a public ledger.

00:05:50.330 --> 00:05:52.930
It's a public record
of transactions.

00:05:52.930 --> 00:05:56.110
And the reason why banks get
interested-- well, have become

00:05:56.110 --> 00:05:59.530
interested in the blockchain--
is because all the bank is,

00:05:59.530 --> 00:06:01.600
to caricature them, is a ledger.

00:06:01.600 --> 00:06:04.270
They have databases, lots
and lots of databases,

00:06:04.270 --> 00:06:05.710
to contain the ledger.

00:06:05.710 --> 00:06:08.890
And they spend a
lot of resources

00:06:08.890 --> 00:06:12.670
overnight reconciling all
their internal ledgers

00:06:12.670 --> 00:06:14.170
with the ledgers of others.

00:06:17.352 --> 00:06:20.440
And you need a complete record,
because, of course, your bank

00:06:20.440 --> 00:06:23.560
balance unfortunately
isn't dependent on just

00:06:23.560 --> 00:06:25.300
your last transaction.

00:06:25.300 --> 00:06:27.580
It's dependent on all
of your transactions.

00:06:27.580 --> 00:06:29.510
So that's why you need a ledger.

00:06:29.510 --> 00:06:31.190
Now, the reason
why Santander think

00:06:31.190 --> 00:06:33.670
they'll save a lot of money
is, rather than spending

00:06:33.670 --> 00:06:36.700
a lot of effort in
reconciling literally hundreds

00:06:36.700 --> 00:06:40.384
or thousands of databases
of ledgers internally

00:06:40.384 --> 00:06:41.800
and with the other
banks, there'll

00:06:41.800 --> 00:06:45.610
be one global source
of truth that everyone

00:06:45.610 --> 00:06:47.710
can point to and
say, yes, that is

00:06:47.710 --> 00:06:49.810
the public record
of our transactions,

00:06:49.810 --> 00:06:50.820
and we all trust it.

00:06:54.330 --> 00:06:55.990
This talk is not
very technical, but I

00:06:55.990 --> 00:07:00.580
want to introduce the
definitions of some elements,

00:07:00.580 --> 00:07:03.680
just so you know if
you read about them.

00:07:03.680 --> 00:07:06.310
So one is the cryptographic
hash function,

00:07:06.310 --> 00:07:09.250
which you'll hear about
hashes if people tell you

00:07:09.250 --> 00:07:10.780
about blockchains.

00:07:10.780 --> 00:07:12.450
It's a very easy
thing to define.

00:07:12.450 --> 00:07:15.880
So a hash function is, you
take a file of any size--

00:07:15.880 --> 00:07:19.000
they can be very small, they can
be the size of a whole movie--

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:20.500
and you hash it.

00:07:20.500 --> 00:07:23.710
It generates a file
which is always small.

00:07:23.710 --> 00:07:27.700
A string of a fixed length
which is not very big at all.

00:07:27.700 --> 00:07:32.170
If you change any element
of the input file--

00:07:32.170 --> 00:07:35.940
just one pixel in the movie,
or one element of data--

00:07:35.940 --> 00:07:38.200
the hash completely changes.

00:07:38.200 --> 00:07:41.590
So the hash acts like a
thumbprint of the document.

00:07:41.590 --> 00:07:44.719
Take a document of every
size, create its thumbprint,

00:07:44.719 --> 00:07:47.260
the hash, and then you put that
hash on the blockchain, which

00:07:47.260 --> 00:07:48.170
is very small.

00:07:48.170 --> 00:07:49.780
Then people can sign on it.

00:07:49.780 --> 00:07:51.500
And when you take
out whatever it

00:07:51.500 --> 00:07:53.740
is, your document you're
interested in, you can say,

00:07:53.740 --> 00:07:56.277
my big document
matches the thumbprint.

00:07:56.277 --> 00:07:57.860
And the thumbprint
must sign the hash.

00:07:57.860 --> 00:08:00.430
So that's what hashes do.

00:08:00.430 --> 00:08:03.110
So a blockchain is
simply a linked list.

00:08:03.110 --> 00:08:07.450
It's a list of blocks
where every block points

00:08:07.450 --> 00:08:11.140
to the previous
blocks through a hash.

00:08:11.140 --> 00:08:14.740
So one thing that gives you
trust is the hash function.

00:08:14.740 --> 00:08:19.630
If I go back to some part of
that history as the blocks,

00:08:19.630 --> 00:08:24.040
and I make a change, the hash
function will no longer work.

00:08:24.040 --> 00:08:26.080
The linked list will be broken.

00:08:26.080 --> 00:08:29.260
So then you can trust
the whole blockchain

00:08:29.260 --> 00:08:31.690
because every block is
pointed to the hash function.

00:08:31.690 --> 00:08:34.030
So that's one thing
that gives you trust.

00:08:34.030 --> 00:08:36.059
There are other elements
that give you trust

00:08:36.059 --> 00:08:38.590
as well, which I'll talk about.

00:08:38.590 --> 00:08:41.669
Another thing is that
it's peer to peer.

00:08:41.669 --> 00:08:45.980
So if you pull out your
smartphone now, or a tablet,

00:08:45.980 --> 00:08:49.920
or a laptop, and you
run something online,

00:08:49.920 --> 00:08:51.760
the chances are
you're connecting

00:08:51.760 --> 00:08:55.060
to a central database,
a central server.

00:08:55.060 --> 00:08:57.940
Usually something like
Google or Facebook.

00:08:57.940 --> 00:09:00.070
With a blockchain,
it's peer to peer,

00:09:00.070 --> 00:09:03.480
which means if you're a
main player in this space,

00:09:03.480 --> 00:09:07.180
everybody gets a complete
record of the entire blockchain.

00:09:07.180 --> 00:09:09.340
So everybody can check
what everybody else

00:09:09.340 --> 00:09:11.530
is doing to make sure
that nobody else is

00:09:11.530 --> 00:09:14.850
behaving in a bad fashion.

00:09:14.850 --> 00:09:18.090
If you do have a
peer-to-peer system,

00:09:18.090 --> 00:09:19.890
there's the problem
of, who's going

00:09:19.890 --> 00:09:21.990
to produce the next block?

00:09:21.990 --> 00:09:25.170
So we could imagine a
scenario where all of us

00:09:25.170 --> 00:09:26.430
are on the blockchain.

00:09:26.430 --> 00:09:30.225
All of us have one node, and
we all have a complete record.

00:09:30.225 --> 00:09:32.100
But somebody needs to
produce the next block.

00:09:32.100 --> 00:09:34.290
How are they going
to choose them?

00:09:34.290 --> 00:09:37.830
And there's what's called
consensus mechanisms.

00:09:37.830 --> 00:09:41.010
So a way of choosing the
next person, but making it

00:09:41.010 --> 00:09:42.840
somehow fair.

00:09:42.840 --> 00:09:44.310
Another term that
you'll hear about

00:09:44.310 --> 00:09:46.410
is something called a
consensus mechanism,

00:09:46.410 --> 00:09:50.040
and the main one that's used
on platforms such as Bitcoin

00:09:50.040 --> 00:09:52.560
is proof of work.

00:09:52.560 --> 00:09:56.910
Proof of work is a way
of getting entities

00:09:56.910 --> 00:10:00.090
that don't know each other
to collaborate and trust

00:10:00.090 --> 00:10:02.520
each other what's
happening, because it's

00:10:02.520 --> 00:10:04.890
very hard to cheat.

00:10:04.890 --> 00:10:06.750
In many of the blockchains
such as Bitcoin,

00:10:06.750 --> 00:10:08.850
they're what's
called public, which

00:10:08.850 --> 00:10:11.940
means anyone with a
computer can join.

00:10:11.940 --> 00:10:15.300
So what they do is they
have a cryptographic puzzle.

00:10:15.300 --> 00:10:18.084
So there's some puzzle
that you have to solve.

00:10:18.084 --> 00:10:20.250
And the way they designed
the puzzle is the only way

00:10:20.250 --> 00:10:22.650
to solve it is to guess.

00:10:22.650 --> 00:10:27.510
So there's some seed called
the nonce with a function,

00:10:27.510 --> 00:10:31.710
and you guess the x such
that the function magically

00:10:31.710 --> 00:10:33.940
produces a small number.

00:10:33.940 --> 00:10:35.700
And then to make
the puzzle harder,

00:10:35.700 --> 00:10:37.612
you just make the number
smaller and smaller.

00:10:37.612 --> 00:10:39.570
So what happens is you
have all these computers

00:10:39.570 --> 00:10:41.950
around the globe trying
to solve the puzzle.

00:10:41.950 --> 00:10:44.370
And they keep guessing, and
the numbers that come out

00:10:44.370 --> 00:10:45.390
are too big.

00:10:45.390 --> 00:10:48.000
And then at one point,
somebody guesses right,

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:51.355
and then they win the prize
of producing the next block.

00:10:51.355 --> 00:10:53.850
So that's another
element of trust.

00:10:53.850 --> 00:10:57.730
So to cheat, you would
have to go back, recreate

00:10:57.730 --> 00:11:01.540
all the hashes, and resolve
all the proof of work puzzles.

00:11:01.540 --> 00:11:03.270
And because they're
hard to solve,

00:11:03.270 --> 00:11:05.545
you would have to
solve them faster--

00:11:05.545 --> 00:11:08.100
if it was the room--
everyone else in the room.

00:11:08.100 --> 00:11:10.860
And that's another element
that creates trust,

00:11:10.860 --> 00:11:15.730
because you cannot
out-compute everybody else.

00:11:15.730 --> 00:11:16.230
OK.

00:11:16.230 --> 00:11:17.790
So it's basically,
proof of work is

00:11:17.790 --> 00:11:22.440
a way of stopping the one bad
person or bad players doing

00:11:22.440 --> 00:11:23.610
nasty things.

00:11:23.610 --> 00:11:25.710
And it's been
mathematically proven,

00:11:25.710 --> 00:11:32.100
as long as less than 50% of your
colleagues, if less than 50%

00:11:32.100 --> 00:11:34.110
of them are bad, you're OK.

00:11:34.110 --> 00:11:37.020
Once more than 50% of them
are bad, then you're not OK.

00:11:37.020 --> 00:11:41.010
But it's a pretty good
way of ensuring trust.

00:11:41.010 --> 00:11:44.720
One negative side effect
of this is something

00:11:44.720 --> 00:11:46.800
that's called bitcoin mining.

00:11:46.800 --> 00:11:50.550
So imagine all these machines
trying to solve these puzzles,

00:11:50.550 --> 00:11:52.482
and everybody wants
to create a new block.

00:11:52.482 --> 00:11:54.690
If you create a new block,
you actually get a reward.

00:11:54.690 --> 00:11:57.070
On Bitcoin, you get a coin.

00:11:57.070 --> 00:12:00.810
So this is the largest bitcoin
mine-- or it was time ago--

00:12:00.810 --> 00:12:01.590
in the US.

00:12:01.590 --> 00:12:04.220
And you can see they have
this big farm of machines.

00:12:04.220 --> 00:12:06.060
So they have all
these machines doing

00:12:06.060 --> 00:12:07.590
these cryptographic puzzles.

00:12:07.590 --> 00:12:08.970
And it was computed
at some point

00:12:08.970 --> 00:12:14.910
that Bitcoin is maybe using
more electricity than Ireland.

00:12:14.910 --> 00:12:16.860
And it's growing, so
you see that's an issue.

00:12:16.860 --> 00:12:20.430
So people work on different
consensus mechanisms

00:12:20.430 --> 00:12:22.120
that don't use electricity.

00:12:22.120 --> 00:12:23.620
I won't spend too
much time on this.

00:12:23.620 --> 00:12:24.828
I'll go through this quickly.

00:12:24.828 --> 00:12:26.650
But proof of work
is the most common.

00:12:26.650 --> 00:12:28.610
So who has the most
computing power?

00:12:28.610 --> 00:12:29.880
Who can solve the puzzles?

00:12:29.880 --> 00:12:32.730
There are others.

00:12:32.730 --> 00:12:34.530
Who has the most capacity?

00:12:34.530 --> 00:12:37.170
The more disc storage
you give, the bigger

00:12:37.170 --> 00:12:40.090
your chance of
winning the prize.

00:12:40.090 --> 00:12:41.250
Proof of stake.

00:12:41.250 --> 00:12:43.140
You take some of your coins.

00:12:43.140 --> 00:12:45.760
You lock them away and
say, I will never use them.

00:12:45.760 --> 00:12:47.790
The more coins you
lock away, the greater

00:12:47.790 --> 00:12:52.470
your chance of producing
the next block.

00:12:52.470 --> 00:12:53.340
Proof of burn.

00:12:53.340 --> 00:12:56.500
I take some coins and I
actually set fire to them.

00:12:56.500 --> 00:12:57.270
Literally.

00:12:57.270 --> 00:12:59.220
And then that gives me a stake.

00:12:59.220 --> 00:13:02.550
So this is all about, if you
want to play in the game,

00:13:02.550 --> 00:13:04.800
prove that you're engaged.

00:13:04.800 --> 00:13:09.210
And that should make
the bad people shy away,

00:13:09.210 --> 00:13:11.830
because they won't be as
engaged as the others.

00:13:11.830 --> 00:13:13.530
There is one of elapsed time.

00:13:13.530 --> 00:13:15.360
Who's been waiting the longest?

00:13:15.360 --> 00:13:22.080
And then there are proof of
authority networks where--

00:13:22.080 --> 00:13:24.660
these are not open
anymore, but you only

00:13:24.660 --> 00:13:26.860
let certain machines go in.

00:13:26.860 --> 00:13:29.280
So certain banks, if
they want to collaborate,

00:13:29.280 --> 00:13:31.680
may only let other banks go in.

00:13:31.680 --> 00:13:34.290
So these are called
permissioned blockchains.

00:13:34.290 --> 00:13:36.700
As opposed to completely
open blockchains,

00:13:36.700 --> 00:13:38.070
anyone can join the party.

00:13:40.920 --> 00:13:43.420
Everything is
controlled by accounts.

00:13:43.420 --> 00:13:48.160
So there are public
and private keys.

00:13:48.160 --> 00:13:52.860
I won't labour this, but
everyone has two keys.

00:13:52.860 --> 00:13:55.420
Your public key, you
share with anyone.

00:13:55.420 --> 00:13:58.140
And that can be used to
encrypt secret messages.

00:13:58.140 --> 00:14:00.990
You keep your private
key in a secret place,

00:14:00.990 --> 00:14:03.860
and that's the key for unlocking
anything that was unencrypted.

00:14:03.860 --> 00:14:05.610
So anything that happens
on the blockchain

00:14:05.610 --> 00:14:09.060
is always signed with somebody
using their private key.

00:14:09.060 --> 00:14:12.210
So you know, in principle, who's
carried out any transaction

00:14:12.210 --> 00:14:12.930
of any sort.

00:14:12.930 --> 00:14:14.660
And that's another
element of trust.

00:14:17.850 --> 00:14:22.290
The most popular blockchain
platform after Bitcoin

00:14:22.290 --> 00:14:24.160
is Ethereum.

00:14:24.160 --> 00:14:27.910
Ethereum has a couple of
interesting extra things.

00:14:27.910 --> 00:14:31.030
So I said that the blockchain
is only a public ledger.

00:14:31.030 --> 00:14:33.330
Ethereum adds another element.

00:14:33.330 --> 00:14:35.240
So it has two types of accounts.

00:14:35.240 --> 00:14:37.410
These normal accounts
for transferring funds.

00:14:37.410 --> 00:14:41.380
And then it has something
called a smart contract.

00:14:41.380 --> 00:14:44.160
So the interesting
about smart contract,

00:14:44.160 --> 00:14:45.515
it is a piece of code.

00:14:45.515 --> 00:14:47.390
So instead of putting
data on the blockchain,

00:14:47.390 --> 00:14:48.700
they put a piece of code.

00:14:48.700 --> 00:14:54.460
And in principle, this code can
embody any legal or financial

00:14:54.460 --> 00:14:55.515
contract.

00:14:55.515 --> 00:14:57.970
So then I have my
blockchain running,

00:14:57.970 --> 00:15:00.820
and it can be running financial
and legal contracts for me

00:15:00.820 --> 00:15:03.700
in the trusted fashion,
transferring funds

00:15:03.700 --> 00:15:04.837
across the globe.

00:15:04.837 --> 00:15:06.670
And again, there are
many interesting things

00:15:06.670 --> 00:15:07.711
that we can do with that.

00:15:07.711 --> 00:15:10.520
So some of the applications
that I mentioned previously--

00:15:10.520 --> 00:15:13.330
so for example, the one with
the car and the car keys--

00:15:13.330 --> 00:15:15.820
was running with
smart contracts.

00:15:15.820 --> 00:15:18.370
On top of that, people
build applications

00:15:18.370 --> 00:15:20.890
as combinations of
smart contracts.

00:15:20.890 --> 00:15:23.560
Instead of calling
these apps, they're

00:15:23.560 --> 00:15:28.180
called dapps, for
decentralised applications.

00:15:28.180 --> 00:15:30.250
And then there are
special browsers.

00:15:30.250 --> 00:15:33.730
So in the way that one can
have a browser for browsing all

00:15:33.730 --> 00:15:36.760
your movies, or browsing
your applications,

00:15:36.760 --> 00:15:42.020
you can browse your dapps in
a special blockchain browser.

00:15:42.020 --> 00:15:43.640
OK.

00:15:43.640 --> 00:15:46.270
There's a great
website called "How

00:15:46.270 --> 00:15:51.340
to Avoid Pointless Blockchain
Projects" for the sceptical.

00:15:51.340 --> 00:15:53.410
And this talks about
the various things

00:15:53.410 --> 00:15:54.760
that you need for a blockchain.

00:15:54.760 --> 00:15:57.250
So as with anything,
you do get some hype,

00:15:57.250 --> 00:15:59.230
and then people
will try to apply

00:15:59.230 --> 00:16:00.580
a blockchain to everything.

00:16:00.580 --> 00:16:02.835
So the main
characteristics you need

00:16:02.835 --> 00:16:04.600
for when a blockchain
will be useful,

00:16:04.600 --> 00:16:06.680
you should need to share data.

00:16:06.680 --> 00:16:08.800
If you don't want to
share data, forget it.

00:16:08.800 --> 00:16:10.830
You should have
multiple writers.

00:16:10.830 --> 00:16:13.970
So multiple people want
to write that data.

00:16:13.970 --> 00:16:16.030
There should be an
absence of trust.

00:16:16.030 --> 00:16:18.100
It's not the case that
everybody trusts everybody

00:16:18.100 --> 00:16:19.660
else completely.

00:16:19.660 --> 00:16:22.360
And your transactions
should interact, ideally.

00:16:22.360 --> 00:16:24.830
As I said, with
your bank balance,

00:16:24.830 --> 00:16:26.352
it's the combination
of transactions

00:16:26.352 --> 00:16:28.060
that give you your
bank balance, not just

00:16:28.060 --> 00:16:30.640
your last spend or last income.

00:16:30.640 --> 00:16:32.430
And then there should
be a set of rules.

00:16:32.430 --> 00:16:34.750
You should not be
completely anarchic.

00:16:34.750 --> 00:16:37.390
Some people should care about
the rules and the assets

00:16:37.390 --> 00:16:41.640
that you're transferring,
be that coins, or diamonds,

00:16:41.640 --> 00:16:42.460
et cetera.

00:16:42.460 --> 00:16:44.730
And something should
back the assets

00:16:44.730 --> 00:16:46.510
where there is a
community, or whoever.

00:16:49.270 --> 00:16:53.550
So a couple of the more
outlandish elements

00:16:53.550 --> 00:16:58.550
that we have that people are
working on with blockchains.

00:16:58.550 --> 00:17:02.360
Two of them I'll talk
about are DAOs and ICOs.

00:17:02.360 --> 00:17:07.690
So a DAO is a distributed
autonomous organisation.

00:17:07.690 --> 00:17:10.839
So I have this blockchain,
which everyone trusts.

00:17:10.839 --> 00:17:12.520
I have smart contracts.

00:17:12.520 --> 00:17:15.250
And these are running with
no humans in the loop.

00:17:15.250 --> 00:17:17.349
And they're transferring assets.

00:17:17.349 --> 00:17:19.310
So some people are thinking, OK.

00:17:19.310 --> 00:17:21.260
I can create a company.

00:17:21.260 --> 00:17:24.670
A company that trades
with no humans.

00:17:24.670 --> 00:17:25.920
Why do we need humans anymore?

00:17:25.920 --> 00:17:27.339
They're not always trustworthy.

00:17:27.339 --> 00:17:29.770
And this will run,
and we can look

00:17:29.770 --> 00:17:32.230
at the record of what
happens on the blockchain.

00:17:32.230 --> 00:17:37.790
So there was something
called The DAO,

00:17:37.790 --> 00:17:39.760
I guess over a
year ago, which was

00:17:39.760 --> 00:17:42.900
acting like a venture capitalist
running on the Ethereum

00:17:42.900 --> 00:17:44.200
blockchain.

00:17:44.200 --> 00:17:49.420
This had, at one point, $160
million worth of investment.

00:17:49.420 --> 00:17:50.860
Crowd-funded.

00:17:50.860 --> 00:17:57.070
And it was parcelling that
money out to various projects

00:17:57.070 --> 00:18:01.185
with no humans using small
contracts on the blockchain.

00:18:01.185 --> 00:18:05.710
There's an interesting
element where

00:18:05.710 --> 00:18:09.130
you can think about
combining any physical object

00:18:09.130 --> 00:18:10.540
with a blockchain platform.

00:18:10.540 --> 00:18:13.630
So then one can think about
turning any physical thing--

00:18:13.630 --> 00:18:16.090
maybe this theatre,
maybe a screen--

00:18:16.090 --> 00:18:18.430
into a company that trades.

00:18:18.430 --> 00:18:20.470
And it rents itself out.

00:18:20.470 --> 00:18:23.410
So you can think about
a car leasing company

00:18:23.410 --> 00:18:25.780
with no humans on the loop.

00:18:25.780 --> 00:18:33.400
IBM, they had a washing machine
that would order its own powder

00:18:33.400 --> 00:18:34.290
when it run out.

00:18:34.290 --> 00:18:37.310
And when it thought that
it was going to break down,

00:18:37.310 --> 00:18:40.690
it would contact an engineer,
pay the engineer for the work,

00:18:40.690 --> 00:18:41.640
and carry on.

00:18:41.640 --> 00:18:43.480
Again, with no
humans in the loop.

00:18:43.480 --> 00:18:47.100
So again, different
things one can think of.

00:18:47.100 --> 00:18:50.980
ICOs are something
in contrast to what

00:18:50.980 --> 00:18:52.579
you see on the stock exchange.

00:18:52.579 --> 00:18:54.370
So when somebody wants
to set up a company,

00:18:54.370 --> 00:18:56.530
they have an initial
public offering.

00:18:56.530 --> 00:18:58.670
So I say, I have
a fantastic idea.

00:18:58.670 --> 00:18:59.450
I have a company.

00:18:59.450 --> 00:19:00.400
Why don't you invest?

00:19:00.400 --> 00:19:01.870
Please invest in me.

00:19:01.870 --> 00:19:04.930
People invest in certain
funds, and for that, they

00:19:04.930 --> 00:19:08.180
get shares in the future
profit of the company.

00:19:08.180 --> 00:19:10.314
So you can think about the
shareholders investing.

00:19:10.314 --> 00:19:11.980
And then, some point
later, you actually

00:19:11.980 --> 00:19:14.390
build your product,
whatever it is.

00:19:14.390 --> 00:19:16.000
And then you start selling.

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:18.200
Users pay you for
those services.

00:19:18.200 --> 00:19:21.970
Now, in that context, you
have two types of stakeholders

00:19:21.970 --> 00:19:23.050
to caricature it.

00:19:23.050 --> 00:19:25.480
You have the users
paying for services,

00:19:25.480 --> 00:19:28.450
and you have stakeholders, which
are somehow-- in one aspect,

00:19:28.450 --> 00:19:30.500
you say, well, they're
syphoning off the money

00:19:30.500 --> 00:19:32.719
for the initial
funds they put in.

00:19:32.719 --> 00:19:34.510
With a blockchain,
there's something called

00:19:34.510 --> 00:19:36.262
an initial coin offering.

00:19:36.262 --> 00:19:37.720
So one interesting
thing one can do

00:19:37.720 --> 00:19:39.303
with a blockchain
is you can basically

00:19:39.303 --> 00:19:41.390
invent your own currency.

00:19:41.390 --> 00:19:43.360
So I can invent
the John currency

00:19:43.360 --> 00:19:44.950
for my fantastic product.

00:19:44.950 --> 00:19:49.090
And I can say, you can
buy the John currency.

00:19:49.090 --> 00:19:54.310
It only costs you 5 pounds
for every John coin.

00:19:54.310 --> 00:19:56.930
You buy that, but it's
really an investment,

00:19:56.930 --> 00:19:58.360
because I don't
have the service.

00:19:58.360 --> 00:20:00.160
But you trust me,
and my services

00:20:00.160 --> 00:20:02.120
will come in the future.

00:20:02.120 --> 00:20:04.930
So when my services come,
users will pay for them.

00:20:04.930 --> 00:20:07.420
And then all of the
John coins you bought

00:20:07.420 --> 00:20:08.860
will be worth something.

00:20:08.860 --> 00:20:12.430
So then we have an ecosystem
with users-- and somehow--

00:20:12.430 --> 00:20:14.660
stakeholders and shareholders.

00:20:14.660 --> 00:20:16.970
But there aren't really
any shareholders.

00:20:16.970 --> 00:20:19.240
So you can take out
the middle player.

00:20:19.240 --> 00:20:21.160
It all runs on the blockchain.

00:20:21.160 --> 00:20:25.600
And there is no
shareholder syphoning off.

00:20:25.600 --> 00:20:29.020
There are just different
elements using the John coin.

00:20:29.020 --> 00:20:32.500
And the John coin stays
in the whole ecosystem.

00:20:32.500 --> 00:20:33.010
OK.

00:20:33.010 --> 00:20:36.910
So let me just have
some closing remarks.

00:20:36.910 --> 00:20:40.160
So of course, some of what
I said maybe intentionally

00:20:40.160 --> 00:20:42.550
is a bit provocative,
a bit outlandish.

00:20:42.550 --> 00:20:44.760
But think about
the current world

00:20:44.760 --> 00:20:48.430
that you live in now, where
every time you take out

00:20:48.430 --> 00:20:51.640
your device, you're connecting
to some central server

00:20:51.640 --> 00:20:52.630
that you've never seen.

00:20:52.630 --> 00:20:56.560
Some database somewhere
that you don't control.

00:20:56.560 --> 00:21:00.800
And there are some big companies
now, big tech companies,

00:21:00.800 --> 00:21:03.070
that have a lot of data on you.

00:21:03.070 --> 00:21:05.740
Tim Berners-Lee, the
Sir Tim Berners-Lee

00:21:05.740 --> 00:21:07.570
who invented the web,
he had an article

00:21:07.570 --> 00:21:11.590
in Vanity Fair in August
where he postulated

00:21:11.590 --> 00:21:15.490
that the web is now
anti-human because of this

00:21:15.490 --> 00:21:17.400
over centralization of data.

00:21:17.400 --> 00:21:21.790
And he's in fact working on
technologies to alleviate this,

00:21:21.790 --> 00:21:23.840
and we're connecting
to his software

00:21:23.840 --> 00:21:28.660
to connect it to our blockchain
at the Open University.

00:21:28.660 --> 00:21:31.210
There was a journalist
in The Guardian

00:21:31.210 --> 00:21:36.030
who asked Google, please send me
all the data you have about me.

00:21:36.030 --> 00:21:40.117
So Google had 5.5 gigabytes'
worth of data on him.

00:21:40.117 --> 00:21:41.950
Now, of course, you can
change your settings

00:21:41.950 --> 00:21:43.120
in different ways.

00:21:43.120 --> 00:21:48.020
I assume that his settings
were the least restricted.

00:21:48.020 --> 00:21:51.160
But Google knew
everywhere he had been.

00:21:51.160 --> 00:21:53.810
They knew about his searches,
including those deleted.

00:21:53.810 --> 00:21:56.320
They knew his
activity on YouTube.

00:21:56.320 --> 00:21:58.450
Now, with a blockchain
and other technologies,

00:21:58.450 --> 00:22:01.780
we can think about creating
a different type of internet

00:22:01.780 --> 00:22:07.980
or web where the data is
shared in a more equal fashion.

00:22:07.980 --> 00:22:10.380
There's also another
case where you

00:22:10.380 --> 00:22:12.120
can think about
people suffering not

00:22:12.120 --> 00:22:14.220
for the over-centralization
of data,

00:22:14.220 --> 00:22:16.860
but because there's a
lack of data on them.

00:22:16.860 --> 00:22:20.550
I read a statistic recently
that 30% of citizens in the US

00:22:20.550 --> 00:22:25.560
cannot get credit because they
have no work history and no

00:22:25.560 --> 00:22:26.310
credit history.

00:22:28.990 --> 00:22:31.800
In the UK, we can think
about the Windrush scandal

00:22:31.800 --> 00:22:33.190
that people were deported.

00:22:33.190 --> 00:22:36.280
And one can view that problem
as a problem with data.

00:22:36.280 --> 00:22:37.900
They didn't have
the data to prove

00:22:37.900 --> 00:22:41.470
that they had been in the UK
for every year for the last 50

00:22:41.470 --> 00:22:41.970
years.

00:22:41.970 --> 00:22:43.969
The government actually
burned some of the data.

00:22:43.969 --> 00:22:44.890
It didn't help.

00:22:44.890 --> 00:22:46.510
So you can think
about alleviating

00:22:46.510 --> 00:22:48.250
some of the social
justice issues

00:22:48.250 --> 00:22:50.470
around data which
may be exacerbated

00:22:50.470 --> 00:22:54.457
by data through technology
such as the blockchain.

