that she has done her duty,

00:25:49.080 --> 00:25:51.750
but actually, it's her
brother that did it?

00:25:51.750 --> 00:25:54.590
How can we tell-- how
can the parents tell--

00:25:54.590 --> 00:25:55.950
who is lying and who is not?

00:25:55.950 --> 00:25:57.900
So at the end of
the day, they still

00:25:57.900 --> 00:26:01.480
have to play police and
actually monitor the children.

00:26:01.480 --> 00:26:03.270
And this is very tiring.

00:26:03.270 --> 00:26:07.950
So the question is
how to help parents.

00:26:07.950 --> 00:26:11.470
Well, actually,
blockchain is the answer.

00:26:11.470 --> 00:26:12.330
[AUDIENCE CHUCKLING]

00:26:12.330 --> 00:26:14.400
I know.

00:26:14.400 --> 00:26:15.840
So they go to the supermarket.

00:26:15.840 --> 00:26:16.940
They buy a blockchain.

00:26:16.940 --> 00:26:18.810
Yes, you can find it everywhere.

00:26:18.810 --> 00:26:21.750
So it is basically just
a transparent tube,

00:26:21.750 --> 00:26:23.490
and you put it in
your kitchen floor

00:26:23.490 --> 00:26:26.570
with some cement around it.

00:26:26.570 --> 00:26:29.040
I'm giving you the
recipe of blockchain.

00:26:29.040 --> 00:26:30.870
You give some tokens
to your children.

00:26:30.870 --> 00:26:32.670
Each colour for one child.

00:26:32.670 --> 00:26:35.640
And you give them a
padlock and a key.

00:26:35.640 --> 00:26:36.757
So why is that?

00:26:36.757 --> 00:26:38.340
If you think about
everything you just

00:26:38.340 --> 00:26:40.260
heard about
blockchain, actually,

00:26:40.260 --> 00:26:43.470
this is a metaphor of
what blockchain is.

00:26:43.470 --> 00:26:45.330
The transparency of
the tube is important,

00:26:45.330 --> 00:26:47.937
because in the
public blockchains,

00:26:47.937 --> 00:26:49.020
everything is transparent.

00:26:49.020 --> 00:26:50.820
You can actually read
every transaction

00:26:50.820 --> 00:26:53.610
on that ledger is
replicated on every node

00:26:53.610 --> 00:26:55.230
of the peer-to-peer network.

00:26:55.230 --> 00:26:57.800
This is one of the greatest
attribute of blockchain.

00:26:57.800 --> 00:27:00.150
The second series is the cement.

00:27:00.150 --> 00:27:02.070
We've been talking
about hashes earlier.

00:27:02.070 --> 00:27:03.390
Hash function.

00:27:03.390 --> 00:27:06.660
The thing that actually links
every block in the blockchain

00:27:06.660 --> 00:27:08.809
and make it not corruptible.

00:27:08.809 --> 00:27:09.600
This is the cement.

00:27:09.600 --> 00:27:12.630
You cannot take the
tube and shake it,

00:27:12.630 --> 00:27:15.270
or remove some of the
tokens of the children.

00:27:15.270 --> 00:27:18.300
Each token is like a transaction
or a block, if you want.

00:27:18.300 --> 00:27:21.450
And then the padlock and the key
is the cryptographic elements.

00:27:21.450 --> 00:27:24.450
Cryptography is one of the
core element of blockchain.

00:27:24.450 --> 00:27:27.870
You cannot interact on a
blockchain if you cannot sign

00:27:27.870 --> 00:27:30.360
your transaction, so you need
your public and private key

00:27:30.360 --> 00:27:33.180
to do so to express yourself.

00:27:33.180 --> 00:27:36.030
And no one else can do it,
because no one else has

00:27:36.030 --> 00:27:39.210
your private key, which is
why every time you will hear

00:27:39.210 --> 00:27:41.970
about blockchain,
the first advice is,

00:27:41.970 --> 00:27:43.137
don't lose your private key.

00:27:43.137 --> 00:27:44.678
Because if you lose
your private key,

00:27:44.678 --> 00:27:46.980
you lose everything,
especially your bitcoins.

00:27:46.980 --> 00:27:48.420
And it happens a lot of time.

00:27:48.420 --> 00:27:50.294
I don't know if you
heard about that man that

00:27:50.294 --> 00:27:53.100
went into a garbage trying
to look for the hard drive,

00:27:53.100 --> 00:27:54.690
and he had some private key.

00:27:54.690 --> 00:27:57.600
Because now he's a millionaire,
but actually, he's not.

00:27:57.600 --> 00:27:59.288
So.

00:27:59.288 --> 00:28:02.710
So this tube was
actually built, and it

00:28:02.710 --> 00:28:06.580
was shown at a hackathon
I organised in 2016.

00:28:06.580 --> 00:28:07.900
Designers worked on it.

00:28:07.900 --> 00:28:09.520
They have no
technical background,

00:28:09.520 --> 00:28:12.340
but they were able to
build this metaphor, which

00:28:12.340 --> 00:28:15.940
is that the sister and
brother are actually society.

00:28:15.940 --> 00:28:17.560
We have millions of
sister and brother

00:28:17.560 --> 00:28:20.020
that are trying to
collaborate, to work together.

00:28:20.020 --> 00:28:22.400
But they cannot always
trust each other.

00:28:22.400 --> 00:28:23.440
So what do we do?

00:28:23.440 --> 00:28:25.420
We add third parties.

00:28:25.420 --> 00:28:26.530
We add middlemen.

00:28:26.530 --> 00:28:27.910
We add authorities.

00:28:27.910 --> 00:28:29.470
And after that, they
take everything.

00:28:29.470 --> 00:28:30.550
They take the value.

00:28:30.550 --> 00:28:31.641
Think about Uber.

00:28:31.641 --> 00:28:33.640
I don't know if you had
the same issue in the UK

00:28:33.640 --> 00:28:36.580
as we had in France, but
it was almost a revolution.

00:28:36.580 --> 00:28:40.020
People were burning
tyres in the subway--

00:28:40.020 --> 00:28:42.460
in the outer roads
and highway, actually.

00:28:42.460 --> 00:28:44.680
They were actually
throwing things

00:28:44.680 --> 00:28:47.410
at people, customer
from the Uber.

00:28:47.410 --> 00:28:49.030
So it went very bad.

00:28:49.030 --> 00:28:49.570
Why?

00:28:49.570 --> 00:28:52.360
Because they felt like
they've been losing their job.

00:28:52.360 --> 00:28:53.530
And why is that?

00:28:53.530 --> 00:28:57.160
Because Uber basically
took over the market.

00:28:57.160 --> 00:28:59.710
But at the same
time, the drivers,

00:28:59.710 --> 00:29:03.390
they could have organised an
Uber in the form of the DAO,

00:29:03.390 --> 00:29:05.320
for example, and say, OK.

00:29:05.320 --> 00:29:06.160
We have the cars.

00:29:06.160 --> 00:29:07.090
We have the expertise.

00:29:07.090 --> 00:29:07.923
We have the network.

00:29:07.923 --> 00:29:08.770
We have the clients.

00:29:08.770 --> 00:29:10.330
Why do we need someone else?

00:29:10.330 --> 00:29:11.500
But they didn't do that.

00:29:11.500 --> 00:29:13.390
They kept doing the same way.

00:29:13.390 --> 00:29:17.060
And Uber added an added value
with a better algorithm.

00:29:17.060 --> 00:29:18.250
And now they control--

00:29:18.250 --> 00:29:19.570
they own the driver.

00:29:19.570 --> 00:29:20.410
They own the margin.

00:29:20.410 --> 00:29:23.410
They calculate everything,
and nobody can say nothing.

00:29:23.410 --> 00:29:26.230
So every time you don't take,
let's say, your own fate

00:29:26.230 --> 00:29:29.680
into your hands, then you're
letting room for someone else

00:29:29.680 --> 00:29:31.950
to do it.

00:29:31.950 --> 00:29:33.340
OK.

00:29:33.340 --> 00:29:35.650
So why is blockchain
interesting?

00:29:35.650 --> 00:29:39.280
Because blockchain, it
is not just a new tech.

00:29:39.280 --> 00:29:41.180
It is not a software.

00:29:41.180 --> 00:29:42.730
It's nothing like that.

00:29:42.730 --> 00:29:44.980
It's a social and
technical paradigm shift.

00:29:44.980 --> 00:29:46.940
It's a new way of
building things.

00:29:46.940 --> 00:29:48.280
And it's not just about finance.

00:29:48.280 --> 00:29:51.466
It's not just about bitcoin,
and darknet, and speculation,

00:29:51.466 --> 00:29:52.840
and greed, and
everything we like

00:29:52.840 --> 00:29:56.000
to read about in the newspaper.

00:29:56.000 --> 00:29:57.610
It's just like the internet.

00:29:57.610 --> 00:30:01.060
When the internet was born,
it started quite slowly.

00:30:01.060 --> 00:30:04.600
People didn't even understand
what was the internet.

00:30:04.600 --> 00:30:07.990
I recommend you to
watch some old video

00:30:07.990 --> 00:30:11.380
about people talking about what
is the internet on TV shows

00:30:11.380 --> 00:30:12.780
and things like that.

00:30:12.780 --> 00:30:13.610
It's super funny.

00:30:13.610 --> 00:30:15.610
They don't even know what
they're talking about.

00:30:15.610 --> 00:30:18.040
This is us right now
talking about blockchain.

00:30:18.040 --> 00:30:20.950
And we have to be patient,
because it takes years for us

00:30:20.950 --> 00:30:24.010
to have a concrete application
of what is internet,

00:30:24.010 --> 00:30:25.397
and what it brings to us.

00:30:25.397 --> 00:30:27.730
So it's going to happen in
the same way with blockchain.

00:30:27.730 --> 00:30:33.110
And the good news is that
it's happening way faster.

00:30:33.110 --> 00:30:36.856
So now I'm going to focus on
one aspect, which is actually

00:30:36.856 --> 00:30:38.230
a good transition
with what we've

00:30:38.230 --> 00:30:40.600
seen at the end of
the last presentation

00:30:40.600 --> 00:30:43.150
about centralization of
data and the question

00:30:43.150 --> 00:30:47.060
of self-sovereignty on data.

00:30:47.060 --> 00:30:49.060
So do you really own
the data you produce?

00:30:49.060 --> 00:30:51.250
I did a presentation at
a technical conference

00:30:51.250 --> 00:30:55.170
a few months ago, and the
title was, "Who Owns You?"

00:30:55.170 --> 00:30:56.950
So I ask this question.

00:30:56.950 --> 00:30:58.920
Nobody told me anything.

00:30:58.920 --> 00:31:00.840
So the answer is, no one.

00:31:00.840 --> 00:31:01.810
That's the answer.

00:31:01.810 --> 00:31:03.240
Nobody owns you.

00:31:03.240 --> 00:31:06.300
But in the reality,
some big players

00:31:06.300 --> 00:31:08.465
of the digital
ecosystem owns you,

00:31:08.465 --> 00:31:09.590
because they own your data.

00:31:09.590 --> 00:31:11.240
They know everything about you.

00:31:11.240 --> 00:31:13.360
People, they are
afraid of hackers.

00:31:13.360 --> 00:31:16.080
I don't know, like
some kind of myth of--

00:31:16.080 --> 00:31:19.260
it's not a myth, but it's
like a minority of the threats

00:31:19.260 --> 00:31:22.230
that we're living in,
like Russian hackers.

00:31:22.230 --> 00:31:24.720
Like East European hackers
entering everywhere.

00:31:24.720 --> 00:31:26.460
But this is not
the biggest threat.

00:31:26.460 --> 00:31:30.600
The biggest threat is the data
that you're actually giving.

00:31:30.600 --> 00:31:32.700
Like, you are giving it.

00:31:32.700 --> 00:31:35.940
Nobody is actually forcing you
or breaking into your computer

00:31:35.940 --> 00:31:37.320
to make you give it.

00:31:37.320 --> 00:31:39.900
And this is when you use
WhatsApp, when you use

00:31:39.900 --> 00:31:41.220
Instagram, when you use Google.

00:31:41.220 --> 00:31:43.920
When you use all these
friendly application.

00:31:43.920 --> 00:31:46.860
But actually, these
are toxic friends,

00:31:46.860 --> 00:31:49.140
because they are sucking
everything from you,

00:31:49.140 --> 00:31:51.270
and they are not giving
you anything back.

00:31:51.270 --> 00:31:55.360
You're completely out
of the value chain here.

00:31:55.360 --> 00:31:57.900
So let's take a
look at this text.

00:31:57.900 --> 00:32:02.280
This is a piece of terms and
condition from Instagram.

00:32:02.280 --> 00:32:05.850
And just the second paragraph
is like the translation

00:32:05.850 --> 00:32:08.340
in human language,
because, you know.

00:32:08.340 --> 00:32:10.920
So what Instagram is
telling you is that, OK.

00:32:10.920 --> 00:32:13.770
So you own your original
pictures and video.

00:32:13.770 --> 00:32:15.810
But we are allowed
to use them, and we

00:32:15.810 --> 00:32:19.710
can let others use them as
well anywhere around the world.

00:32:19.710 --> 00:32:22.260
And also, people might
pay us to use them,

00:32:22.260 --> 00:32:24.480
and we will not
pay you for that.

00:32:24.480 --> 00:32:25.910
Awesome, right?

00:32:25.910 --> 00:32:27.070
[AUDIENCE CHUCKLING]

00:32:27.070 --> 00:32:27.920
Great.

00:32:27.920 --> 00:32:30.530
And what do we do every
time we download an app?

00:32:30.530 --> 00:32:31.190
We press Yes.

00:32:31.190 --> 00:32:31.790
Why?

00:32:31.790 --> 00:32:33.410
Because we need the service.

00:32:33.410 --> 00:32:36.170
So we are in a paradigm
that is very simple--

00:32:36.170 --> 00:32:39.380
and I don't know why we believe
it's how things should be--

00:32:39.380 --> 00:32:41.510
where, when we
need to service, we

00:32:41.510 --> 00:32:44.120
are ready to sacrifice
our data to have it.

00:32:44.120 --> 00:32:46.580
And sometimes, we pay.

00:32:46.580 --> 00:32:50.990
This is like a
double punishment.

00:32:50.990 --> 00:32:55.180
So let me introduce you to
some of my research work.

00:32:55.180 --> 00:32:57.580
I've been asking
myself two questions.

00:32:57.580 --> 00:33:00.640
How to give back to the
user control over its data,

00:33:00.640 --> 00:33:02.260
and how to reconcile
transparency

00:33:02.260 --> 00:33:05.350
and confidentiality in a
decentralised environment.

00:33:05.350 --> 00:33:08.200
You have now understand
the hope that

00:33:08.200 --> 00:33:10.450
is in blockchain, the promise.

00:33:10.450 --> 00:33:14.120
But I believe that if we don't
solve the confidentiality

00:33:14.120 --> 00:33:18.580
situation, it's going to be not
as spectacular of a revolution

00:33:18.580 --> 00:33:20.839
as we want.

00:33:20.839 --> 00:33:22.630
One case study that
I'm going to talk about

00:33:22.630 --> 00:33:25.440
is my project, Kidner, which
is a decentralised matching

00:33:25.440 --> 00:33:28.480
platform for kidney transplant.

00:33:28.480 --> 00:33:31.230
So first, critical data.

00:33:31.230 --> 00:33:32.500
What are they?

00:33:32.500 --> 00:33:34.110
So we can found them everywhere.

00:33:34.110 --> 00:33:37.440
It's personal data,
medical data, crisis data,

00:33:37.440 --> 00:33:39.270
business data, bank data.

00:33:39.270 --> 00:33:43.860
And I don't know if you know
that, but take a look at this.

00:33:43.860 --> 00:33:46.870
The data that are the most
expensive and the most

00:33:46.870 --> 00:33:50.160
searched for by malicious
person are medical data.

00:33:50.160 --> 00:33:52.630
Don't know if you knew that.

00:33:52.630 --> 00:33:55.230
That's scary.

00:33:55.230 --> 00:33:57.980
So Kidner is about
using blockchain

00:33:57.980 --> 00:33:59.700
in a health care
environment, which

00:33:59.700 --> 00:34:01.950
is kind of the worst
thing if you're

00:34:01.950 --> 00:34:04.080
building a startup or an
entrepreneurship project

00:34:04.080 --> 00:34:06.640
to start with because of
all the legal complication

00:34:06.640 --> 00:34:08.130
and ethical complication.

00:34:08.130 --> 00:34:11.198
But I believe if you can solve
this, we can solve everything.

00:34:11.198 --> 00:34:13.739
So I'm going to introduce you
to the concept of Kidner, which

00:34:13.739 --> 00:34:16.310
is across the nation.

00:34:16.310 --> 00:34:19.820
So we have Bob and
Alice, like always.

00:34:19.820 --> 00:34:21.040
So Bob needs a kidney.

00:34:21.040 --> 00:34:22.400
He's a recipient.

00:34:22.400 --> 00:34:24.429
Alice wants to give
Bob her kidney.

00:34:24.429 --> 00:34:26.409
She's a donor.

00:34:26.409 --> 00:34:29.739
Unfortunately, Bob and
Alice are not compatible.

00:34:29.739 --> 00:34:33.010
What that mean is that this
transfer cannot happen.

00:34:33.010 --> 00:34:35.710
This might be the end
of the story for them.

00:34:35.710 --> 00:34:36.449
OK.

00:34:36.449 --> 00:34:38.850
Then we have Carol and
Dave on the other side,

00:34:38.850 --> 00:34:41.440
maybe in another country.

00:34:41.440 --> 00:34:43.179
Same situation there.

00:34:43.179 --> 00:34:46.189
What they don't know-- because
it doesn't exist today--

00:34:46.189 --> 00:34:48.480
what they don't know is that,
actually, Alice and Carol

00:34:48.480 --> 00:34:50.820
are compatible, and Dave
and Bob are compatible.

00:34:50.820 --> 00:34:52.710
And you will only
know that if we

00:34:52.710 --> 00:34:55.755
have a pool of pairs
of incompatible donor

00:34:55.755 --> 00:34:59.340
and recipients on a connected
network with algorithm that

00:34:59.340 --> 00:35:01.550
can run to find matches.

00:35:01.550 --> 00:35:02.520
Right?

00:35:02.520 --> 00:35:03.930
So how do we create that?

00:35:03.930 --> 00:35:05.520
To create that,
you need a network

00:35:05.520 --> 00:35:07.715
of hospitals that are
willing to collaborate.

00:35:07.715 --> 00:35:11.160
But they don't want to, because
medical data is sensitive.

00:35:11.160 --> 00:35:14.370
And also, data in general
is sort of precious.

00:35:14.370 --> 00:35:16.870
So people, they don't
want to share that.

00:35:16.870 --> 00:35:21.060
So blockchain here, I'm using
it to solve a governance issue,

00:35:21.060 --> 00:35:23.370
meaning that there is
not one hospital that

00:35:23.370 --> 00:35:26.100
is the authority on
the other hospital.

00:35:26.100 --> 00:35:28.770
There is not one place
where data are stored,

00:35:28.770 --> 00:35:30.920
like for example, in the US.

00:35:30.920 --> 00:35:34.050
What about patients in
France, or Europe, or?

00:35:34.050 --> 00:35:38.010
So if you don't remove
this from the blocks,

00:35:38.010 --> 00:35:40.890
nothing is going to happen
just on a political level.

00:35:40.890 --> 00:35:42.660
So with blockchain,
there's nothing

00:35:42.660 --> 00:35:44.670
such as this, because
every hospital is

00:35:44.670 --> 00:35:47.850
going to run its own node
and store its own data.

00:35:47.850 --> 00:35:49.590
Second thing,
matching algorithm.

00:35:49.590 --> 00:35:52.229
We need to do computation
in a decentralised fashion.

00:35:52.229 --> 00:35:53.520
We can do that with blockchain.

00:35:53.520 --> 00:35:54.960
We've seen it with Ethereum.

00:35:54.960 --> 00:35:58.090
It is the perfect platform to
run decentralised application.

00:35:58.090 --> 00:36:00.090
We also call them
unstoppable application,

00:36:00.090 --> 00:36:03.180
because no one can
actually kill the process.

00:36:03.180 --> 00:36:05.980
Now, the third aspect of
this project is cryptography.

00:36:05.980 --> 00:36:10.460
So I'm working on a cryptosystem
such as homomorphic encryption,

00:36:10.460 --> 00:36:12.300
or a multi-party computation.

00:36:12.300 --> 00:36:16.200
And basically, what it does,
it enables you to compute

00:36:16.200 --> 00:36:19.800
and perform calculation on
data that you cannot see.

00:36:19.800 --> 00:36:21.730
On encrypted data.

00:36:21.730 --> 00:36:23.930
It's also blind computation.

00:36:23.930 --> 00:36:27.300
With my team, we are building
a platform called HellHound.

00:36:27.300 --> 00:36:31.110
And it is a decentralised
platform for blind computation.

00:36:31.110 --> 00:36:35.610
Any startup, any company,
anyone can use HellHound, send

00:36:35.610 --> 00:36:37.910
some encrypted data,
send an algorithm,

00:36:37.910 --> 00:36:40.020
and we're able to
send back the result.

00:36:40.020 --> 00:36:41.790
We don't know what
the result is.

00:36:41.790 --> 00:36:43.286
We don't know what
the inputs are.

00:36:43.286 --> 00:36:44.910
But we're able to
send back the results

00:36:44.910 --> 00:36:47.820
so that it is decrypted
by the end user.

00:36:47.820 --> 00:36:49.500
If you think about
that, that means

00:36:49.500 --> 00:36:52.170
that we don't have anymore
to do the sacrifice

00:36:52.170 --> 00:36:54.190
I was talking about earlier.

00:36:54.190 --> 00:36:57.750
Now, we can use, for example,
23andMe for the genetics.

00:36:57.750 --> 00:36:59.610
The DNA testing.

